================================================================================
DNS, CDN, Load Balancer, API Gateway - Component Level Understanding
================================================================================

1. DNS Behaviour

DNS ka main kaam hota hai:

    Domain Name  ->  IP Address

Example:

    api.example.com  ->  34.120.10.5

DNS bas configured records ke basis par response deta hai.

Common DNS records:

    A Record:
        Domain ko IPv4 address se map karta hai.

        Example:
            api.example.com -> 34.120.10.5

    AAAA Record:
        Domain ko IPv6 address se map karta hai.

        Example:
            api.example.com -> 2400:cb00:2048:1::c629:d7a2

    CNAME Record:
        Ek domain ko doosre domain name se map karta hai.

        Example:
            api.example.com -> my-load-balancer.aws.com

        Is case me DNS resolver recursively ya internally CNAME ko resolve karke
        final IP address nikalta hai.

        Final result eventually IP address hi hota hai.

Usually modern cloud infrastructure me CNAME/Alias records zyada use hote hain,
because cloud resources ke actual IP addresses change ho sakte hain.

================================================================================
CASE 1: Small Monolithic Application on a Single Server
================================================================================

Suppose ek small monolithic application hai jo sirf ek single server par deployed hai.

Is case me DNS resolution ke baad directly server ka IP return hota hai.

Flow:

    User
      |
      | DNS Resolution
      v
    DNS returns Server IP
      |
      v
    Single Server
      |
      v
    Monolithic Application processes the request

Explanation:

    Ye setup small applications, personal projects, ya basic VPS deployments me common hai.

================================================================================
CASE 2: Monolithic Application with Multiple Instances and Load Balancer
================================================================================

Suppose ek monolithic application hai, but uske multiple instances different servers
par run kar rahe hain.

In multiple servers ke traffic ko manage karne ke liye ek Load Balancer configured hai.
Load Balancers generally algorithms like Round Robin, Least Connections, etc. use karke
servers ke beech load balance karte hain.

Is case me DNS resolution ke baad Load Balancer ka IP return hota hai.

Flow:

    User
      |
      v
    DNS
      |
      | returns Load Balancer IP
      v
    Load Balancer
      |
      |------------------|------------------|
      v                  v                  v
    App Instance 1     App Instance 2     App Instance 3

Explanation:

    Load Balancer ka kaam hai traffic ko multiple running instances ke beech
    distribute karna.

    URL routing usually application ke andar hoti hai, like Spring Boot controllers.

Example in Spring Boot:

    /users      -> UserController
    /orders     -> OrderController
    /payments   -> PaymentController

================================================================================
CASE 3: Microservices Architecture with API Gateway and Service Load Balancers
================================================================================

Suppose ek microservices architecture hai jisme multiple services hain.

Example:

    User Service
    Order Service
    Payment Service

Har service ke multiple instances different servers par run kar rahe hain.
Har service ke instances ko manage karne ke liye us service ka apna Load Balancer hai.

Example:

    User Service Load Balancer
    Order Service Load Balancer
    Payment Service Load Balancer

Ab question aata hai:

    Request kis service ke Load Balancer ko bhejni hai?

Iske liye API Gateway use hota hai.

Is case me DNS resolution ke baad API Gateway ka IP return hota hai.

Flow:

    User
      |
      v
    DNS
      |
      | returns API Gateway IP
      v
    API Gateway
      |
      |----------------------|----------------------|
      v                      v                      v
    User Service LB       Order Service LB       Payment Service LB
      |                      |                      |
      v                      v                      v
    User Instances        Order Instances        Payment Instances

Explanation:

    API Gateway ka kaam sirf URL routing nahi hota.
    API Gateway aur bhi kaam karta hai:

        - Authentication
        - Authorization
        - Rate limiting
        - Request routing
        - API versioning
        - Logging
        - Monitoring
        - Request/response transformation

Example routing:

    /users/**     -> User Service Load Balancer
    /orders/**    -> Order Service Load Balancer
    /payments/**  -> Payment Service Load Balancer

================================================================================
CASE 4: Microservices Architecture with CDN + API Gateway + Service Load Balancers
================================================================================

Suppose ek microservices architecture hai jisme multiple services hain,
har service ke multiple instances hain, har service ke paas apna Load Balancer hai,
aur URL routing ke liye API Gateway bhi hai.

Ab system ko optimize karne ke liye CDN add kiya ja sakta hai.

CDN ka full form hai Content Delivery Network.

CDNs basically geographically distributed servers hote hain jo different edge locations
par placed hote hain.

CDN ka main kaam:

    - Static content cache karna
    - Network latency reduce karna
    - Origin server par unnecessary load kam karna
    - Response fast karna

Examples of cacheable content:

    - Images
    - Videos
    - CSS files
    - JavaScript files
    - Public static files

DNS and CDN behaviour:

    Case 4.1: Anycast IP based CDN

        Multiple CDN edge locations same IP address announce kar sakti hain.
        Ye same IP DNS me configured ho sakta hai.

        DNS resolution ke baad CDN ka IP return hota hai.

        Then BGP routing user request ko nearest/optimal CDN edge location par route karti hai.

        Example:

            User in India -> Mumbai/Singapore CDN edge
            User in US    -> US CDN edge

        Same IP ho sakta hai, but network routing nearest CDN edge select kar leti hai.

    Case 4.2: Geo DNS based CDN

        CDN ke different edge locations ke different IPs ho sakte hain.
        DNS resolver user ke approximate location ke basis par nearby CDN IPs return
        kar sakta hai.

        Example:

            User India me hai:
                DNS returns India/Singapore CDN IPs

            User Europe me hai:
                DNS returns Europe CDN IPs

Flow:

    User
      |
      v
    DNS
      |
      | returns CDN IP
      v
    Nearby CDN Edge
      |
      | cache hit
      |------------------> Response returned from CDN
      |
      | cache miss
      v
    API Gateway
      |
      |----------------------|----------------------|
      v                      v                      v
    User Service LB       Order Service LB       Payment Service LB
      |                      |                      |
      v                      v                      v
    User Instances        Order Instances        Payment Instances

Why CDN helps:

    Suppose ek image repeatedly same geographical location se request ho rahi hai.

    Without CDN:

        User -> Server -> Image fetched from origin every time

    With CDN:

        First request:
            CDN image ko origin server se fetch karta hai.

        Subsequent requests:
            CDN same image apne cache se return kar deta hai.

Example:

    Agar image service ka origin server US me hai aur user India me hai,
    to har baar US server tak request bhejna slow hoga.

    CDN use karne se image India/Singapore ke nearby CDN edge se serve ho sakti hai.

